Quantile additive models using qgam and mgcViz

Matteo Fasiolo

October 07 2019

  • 1 Electricity demand forecasting example (1)
  • 2 Some details on the ELF loss
    • 2.1 Setting the loss smoothness manually
    • 2.2 Modelling the loss smoothness and the learning rate
  • 3 Electricity demand forecasting (2): loss-based checks
  • 4 References

The qgam R package offers methods for fitting additive quantile regression models based on splines, using the methods described in Fasiolo et al., 2017. It is useful to use qgam together with mgcViz, which extends the basic visualizations provided by mgcv.

The main fitting functions are:

  • qgam() fits an additive quantile regression model to a single quantile. Very similar to mgcv::gam(). It returns an object of class qgam, which inherits from mgcv::gamObject.
  • mqgam() fits the same additive quantile regression model to several quantiles. It is more efficient that calling qgam() several times, especially in terms of memory usage.
  • qgamV() and mqgamV() are two convenient wrappers that fit quantile GAMs and return gamViz objects, for which mgcViz provides lots of visualizations.

1 Electricity demand forecasting example (1)

We load the data and remove holidays:

library(mgcViz)
data(UKload)
head(UKload)
##     NetDemand       wM   wM_s95       Posan      Dow      Trend
## 25      38353 6.046364 5.558800 0.001369941   samedi 1293879600
## 73      41192 2.803969 3.230582 0.004109824 dimanche 1293966000
## 121     43442 2.097259 1.858198 0.006849706    lundi 1294052400
## 169     50736 3.444187 2.310408 0.009589588    mardi 1294138800
## 217     50438 5.958674 4.724961 0.012329471 mercredi 1294225200
## 265     50064 4.124248 4.589470 0.015069353    jeudi 1294311600
##     NetDemand.48 Holy Year                Date
## 25         38353    1 2011 2011-01-01 12:00:00
## 73         38353    0 2011 2011-01-02 12:00:00
## 121        41192    0 2011 2011-01-03 12:00:00
## 169        43442    0 2011 2011-01-04 12:00:00
## 217        50736    0 2011 2011-01-05 12:00:00
## 265        50438    0 2011 2011-01-06 12:00:00
# Discard Christmas holiday and other holidays
library(lubridate)
Data <- UKload
Data$month <- month(as.POSIXlt(Data$Date, format="%d/%m/%Y"))
Data$day <- day(as.POSIXlt(Data$Date, format="%d/%m/%Y"))
chri <- (Data$month == 12 & Data$day > 20) | (Data$month == 1 & Data$day < 5) | (Data$Holy==1)
Data <- UKload[ !chri, ]

We fit a median QGAM, we get a gamViz object in two different ways:

# Option 1
fit50 <- qgam(NetDemand ~ Dow + NetDemand.48 + s(wM) + s(wM_s95) + s(Trend, k = 4) + s(Posan, k = 30), 
              qu = 0.5,
              data = Data)
## Estimating learning rate. Each dot corresponds to a loss evaluation. 
## qu = 0.5........done
fit50 <- getViz(fit50)  

# Option 2
fit50 <- qgamV(NetDemand ~ Dow + NetDemand.48 + s(wM) + s(wM_s95) + s(Trend, k = 4) + s(Posan, k = 30),
               qu = 0.5,
               data = Data)  
## Estimating learning rate. Each dot corresponds to a loss evaluation. 
## qu = 0.5........done

We can plot all smooth effects:

print(plot(fit50), pages = 1)

We can check whether the proportion of negative residuals changes along Posan:

check1D(fit50, "Posan") + l_gridQCheck1D()

We can check along several variables, because check1D is vectorised:

print(check1D(fit50, list("Posan", "wM", "wM_s95", "Dow")) + l_gridQCheck1D(), pages = 1)

Simularly we can check along two variables:

check2D(fit50, "Posan", "wM") + l_gridQCheck2D(stand = FALSE)

Here we are not standardising, so each bin’s colour represents the proportion of negative residuals in that bin. By default standardisation is used to have an idea of the significance of the deviations from the chosen quantile (0.5 here):

check2D(fit50, "Posan", "wM") + l_gridQCheck2D()

Also check2D is vectorized, here is will check all pairs of variables:

print(check2D(fit50, list("Posan", "wM", "Dow")) + l_gridQCheck2D(), pages = 1)

Now we fit multiple quantiles:

fitAll <- mqgamV(NetDemand ~ Dow + NetDemand.48 + s(wM) + s(wM_s95) + s(Trend, k = 4) + s(Posan, k = 30), 
                 qu = c(0.1, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 0.9),
                 data = Data) 
## Estimating learning rate. Each dot corresponds to a loss evaluation. 
## qu = 0.5........done 
## qu = 0.25..............done 
## qu = 0.75...............done 
## qu = 0.1....................done 
## qu = 0.9...........done

Then we can plot of smooth effects together:

print(plot(fitAll), pages = 1)

Or we can extract one of the smooth effects, and plot it for all quantiles:

plot(sm(fitAll, 4))

We can do the same for parametric terms:

plot(pterm(fitAll, 1))

Here fitAll is just a list of gamViz objects, we can handle them individually:

fit10 <- fitAll[[1]]

print(plot(fit10), pages = 1)

2 Some details on the ELF loss

2.1 Setting the loss smoothness manually

Let’s simulate some data:

set.seed(5235)
n <- 1000
x <- seq(-3, 3, length.out = n)
X <- cbind(1, x, x^2)
beta <- c(0, 1, 1)
f <- drop(X %*% beta)
dat <- f + rgamma(n, 4, 1)
dataf <- data.frame(cbind(dat, x))
names(dataf) <- c("y", "x")

Assume that we want to estimate quantiles 0.05, 0.5 and 0.95:

fit <- mqgamV(y ~ s(x), data = dataf, qu = c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95))
## Estimating learning rate. Each dot corresponds to a loss evaluation. 
## qu = 0.5........done 
## qu = 0.95........done 
## qu = 0.05.................done
plot(x, dat, col = "grey", ylab = "y")
lines(x, f + qgamma(0.95, 4, 1), lty = 2)
lines(x, f + qgamma(0.5, 4, 1), lty = 2)
lines(x, f + qgamma(0.05, 4, 1), lty = 2)
lines(x, predict(fit[[1]]), col = 2)
lines(x, predict(fit[[2]]), col = 2)
lines(x, predict(fit[[3]]), col = 2)

Let’s try to use several values of err:

lfit <- lapply(c(0.01, 0.05, 0.1, 0.2, 0.3, 0.5),
               function(.inp){
                 mqgamV(y ~ s(x), data = dataf, qu = c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95), err = .inp, 
                        aQgam = list(control = list("progress" = F)))
               })

plot(x, dat, col = "grey", ylab = "y", ylim = c(-2, 20))
colss <- rainbow(length(lfit))
for(ii in 1:length(lfit)){
  lines(x, predict(lfit[[ii]][[1]]), col = colss[ii])
  lines(x, predict(lfit[[ii]][[2]]), col = colss[ii])
  lines(x, predict(lfit[[ii]][[3]]), col = colss[ii])
}
lines(x, f + qgamma(0.95, 4, 1), lty = 2)
lines(x, f + qgamma(0.5, 4, 1), lty = 2)
lines(x, f + qgamma(0.05, 4, 1), lty = 2)
legend("top", legend = c(0.01, 0.05, 0.1, 0.2, 0.3, 0.5), lty = 1, col = colss)

The bias increases with err, and it is upward (downward) for high (low) quantiles. The median fit is not much affected by err. The bias really starts appearing for err > 0.1. Decreasing err tends to slow down computation:

system.time( fit1 <- qgamV(y ~ s(x), data = dataf, qu = 0.95, 
                           aQgam = list(control = list("progress" = F))) )[[3]]
## [1] 0.305
system.time( fit2 <- qgamV(y ~ s(x), data = dataf, qu = 0.95, err = 0.001, 
                           aQgam = list(control = list("progress" = F))) )[[3]]
## [1] 29.712

Even worse, it can lead to numeric problems. Here we check that we have found the minimum of the calibration loss:

check(fit1$calibr, sel = 2)

check(fit2$calibr, sel = 2)

In the first case the loss looks smooth and with as single minimum, in the second case we have some instabilities. If the calibration loss looks like this, you generally have to increase err.

2.2 Modelling the loss smoothness and the learning rate

Let us consider the motorcycle data set:

library(MASS)
data(mcycle)
plot(mcycle)

Now we fit a quantile GAM for quantile 0.9

fit09 <- qgam(accel ~ s(times, k=20, bs="ad"), 
              data = mcycle, 
              qu = 0.9)
## Estimating learning rate. Each dot corresponds to a loss evaluation. 
## qu = 0.9....................done

We now plot the quantile with confidence intervals

pred <- predict(fit09, se = TRUE)

plot(mcycle, ylim = c(-140, 85))
lines(mcycle$times, pred$fit)
lines(mcycle$times, pred$fit + 2 * pred$se, col = 2)
lines(mcycle$times, pred$fit - 2 * pred$se, col = 2)

There are two problems with this fit:

  • the confidence intervals have nearly constant width;
  • the estimated quantile is far above the data for times < 15.

We address these issues by modelling the learning rate as well

fit09_2 <- qgam(list(accel ~ s(times, k=20, bs="ad"),
                           ~ s(times)),
                 data = mcycle, 
                 qu = 0.9)
## Estimating learning rate. Each dot corresponds to a loss evaluation. 
## qu = 0.9..........done

Again predict and plot

pred <- predict(fit09_2, se = TRUE)

plot(mcycle, ylim = c(-140, 90))
lines(mcycle$times, pred$fit)
lines(mcycle$times, pred$fit + 2 * pred$se, col = 2)
lines(mcycle$times, pred$fit - 2 * pred$se, col = 2)

Looks much better!

3 Electricity demand forecasting (2): loss-based checks

We divide the data into training and testing set, and we fit an (over-simplified) median GAM:

trainD <- Data[1:1000, ]
testD  <- Data[-(1:1000), ]

fit50 <- qgamV(NetDemand ~ Dow + s(wM, k = 4) + s(wM_s95, k = 4) + s(Trend, k = 4) + s(Posan, k = 4), 
               qu = 0.5,
               data = trainD)
## Estimating learning rate. Each dot corresponds to a loss evaluation. 
## qu = 0.5........done

Then we look at the distribution of the residuals:

check0D(fit50) + l_hist()

Looking at the residuals distribution is pretty useless for QGAM. It is better to look at the pinball loss. To do so we firstly create pinball loss function:

pinball <- function(y, mu, qu){ # mu is fitted quantile, qu is quantile of interest
  tau <- 1 - qu
  d <- y - mu
  l <- d * 0
  l[d < 0] <- - tau*d[d<0]
  l[d > 0] <- - (tau-1)*d[d>0]
  return( l )
}

Then call again check0D, we specify that we are looking at raw observations y, and we transform them to pinball losses:

check0D(fit50, 
        type = "y", 
        trans = function(y, ...) pinball(y, fit50$fitted.values, qu = 0.5)) + 
        l_dens1D() + l_rug() + xlab("Pinball loss") + theme(legend.position="none")

So we have occasional very large losses on the training set. To look at the test set we do:

fit50 <- getViz(fit50, newdata = testD)

This makes so that from now on all checks will be performed on testD, rather than trainD. For instance:

check0D(fit50, 
        type = "y", 
        trans = function(y, ...) pinball(y, predict(fit50, newdata = testD), qu = 0.5)) + 
        l_dens1D() + l_rug() + xlab("Pinball loss") + theme(legend.position="none")

Notice the call to predict on testD data set above.

We can also look at the losses along a variable such as Posan, on the test set:

check1D(fit50, 
        x = "Posan", 
        type = "y", 
        trans = function(y, ...) pinball(y, predict(fit50, newdata = testD), qu = 0.5)) + 
  geom_smooth() + 
  l_gridCheck1D(gridFun = function(x, ...) ifelse(length(x) > 5, mean(x), NA), level = 0) + 
  l_rug() + ylab("Pinball loss")

Give that check1D is vectorised, we can look along several variables by doing:

pl <- check1D(fit50, 
              x = list("Posan", "Dow", "wM_s95", "NetDemand.48"), 
              type = "y", 
              trans = function(y, ...) pinball(y, predict(fit50, newdata = testD), qu = 0.5)) + 
  geom_smooth() + 
  l_gridCheck1D(gridFun = function(x, ...) ifelse(length(x) > 5, mean(x), NA), level = 0) + 
  l_rug() + ylab("Pinball loss")

print(pl, pages = 1)

To get confidence intervals for the pinball loss plot along Dow, we do:

check1D(fit50, 
        x = "Dow", 
        type = "y", 
        trans = function(y, ...) pinball(y, predict(fit50, newdata = testD), qu = 0.5)) + 
  stat_summary(fun.data = "mean_cl_normal", geom = "crossbar") + 
  l_rug() + ylab("Pinball loss")

We can do something similar across two dimensions:

check2D(fit50, "Posan", "wM_s95", 
        type = "y", 
        trans = function(y, ...) pinball(y, predict(fit50, newdata = testD), qu = 0.5)) + 
  l_gridCheck2D(gridFun = function(x, ...) ifelse(length(x) > 5, mean(x), NA), stand = F, bw = c(0.075, 2)) + 
  l_rug() + labs(fill="Loss")

Also here we can exploit vectorization:

pl <- check2D(fit50, list("Posan", "wM_s95", "Dow", "NetDemand.48"), 
              type = "y", 
              trans = function(y, ...) pinball(y, predict(fit50, newdata = testD), qu = 0.5)) + 
  l_gridCheck2D(gridFun = function(x, ...) ifelse(length(x) > 2, mean(x), NA), stand = F) + 
  l_rug() + theme(legend.position="bottom") + labs(fill="Loss")

print(pl, pages = 1)

If you instead want to perform the checks on the training set, you just need to do:

fit50 <- getViz(fit50) # same as  fit50 <- getViz(fit50, newdata = trainD)

check2D(fit50, "Posan", "wM_s95", 
        type = "y", 
        trans = function(y, ...) pinball(y, predict(fit50, newdata = trainD), qu = 0.5)) + 
  l_gridCheck2D(gridFun = function(x, ...) ifelse(length(x) > 5, mean(x), NA), stand = F, bw = c(0.075, 2)) + 
  l_rug() + labs(fill="Loss")

4 References
